<Fragment slot="intro">
<p>Fullerton is a college city — Cal State Fullerton with 40,000 students sits on State College Boulevard in the heart of the city, and Fullerton College adds 20,000 more. That means a large portion of Fullerton's residential population along Harbor Boulevard and the CSUF corridor cycles through apartments every few years, and the LG dryers in those buildings run hard. But Fullerton also has some of the oldest and most well-established residential neighbourhoods in north Orange County — Sunny Hills, Rolling Hills, Raymond Hills, Richman, Maple Park — where families have lived in the same homes since the 1950s and the vent runs have never been professionally assessed. Two completely different service environments in one city, a mile apart and thirty years of maintenance history apart. We navigate both every day.</p>
</Fragment>

<h2>What LG Dryer Calls in Fullerton Actually Look Like</h2>
<p>Fullerton's college-town and established-residential split creates distinct service scenarios by neighbourhood.</p>

<p><strong>Fullerton Hills, Sunny Hills, Rolling Hills — established hillside homes (92835).</strong> The residential communities on the hills in the eastern part of Fullerton — homes from the 1960s and 1970s on streets running above Harbor Boulevard toward the hills. These are the Fullerton calls we know well: long-term owners, machines running reliably for 18–25 years, first thermal fuse failure from vent runs that have accumulated decades of dry inland lint. We had a call on Basque Avenue last month — DLGX from 2004, first service call ever. Vent run hadn't been touched since the home was built in 1972. Cleared the duct with an extended two-pass procedure, replaced the fuse ($280–350), machine back to full performance. Homeowner had owned the home 28 years. Never knew the vent needed cleaning.</p>

<p><strong>Raymond Hills, Richman, Maple Park — original 1950s–1960s housing (92831, 92832).</strong> The original Fullerton residential neighbourhoods on the flat grid — homes from the 1950s and early 1960s in areas like Richman and Maple Park. This is the oldest housing stock in Fullerton. Original vent runs with 50–60 years of accumulated dry inland lint. Multiple owners, multiple appliances, zero professional vent assessments. We use extended two-pass cleaning procedures on these homes. Airflow measured before and after. California code compliance check on any 1950s installation where the configuration looks non-standard. Our technicians arrive with digital multimeters and amp clamps specifically for older Fullerton homes where original wiring configurations sometimes affect heating element performance alongside vent restriction.</p>

<p><strong>CSUF area and college rental corridor — State College Boulevard, Harbor Boulevard (92831, 92832, 92833).</strong> The apartment buildings and rental houses near Cal State Fullerton campus on and around State College Boulevard and Harbor Boulevard. Stacked DLGX/DLEX in laundry closets, shared building vent infrastructure, high-turnover tenants running machines heavily. The highest-intensity dryer use environment in Fullerton. Machines in CSUF-area buildings often run 3–5 loads per day during the academic year. We find persistent d80 codes in CSUF-area buildings that have had multiple individual machine replacements but the building duct has never been cleared. The problem is always the shared duct — never the machine. We separate stacks, clear building vents, restack — 30–45 minutes added, no surcharge.</p>

<p><strong>Amerige Heights and newer western Fullerton (92833).</strong> The planned residential development in western Fullerton — homes from the late 1990s and early 2000s. Better vent installations, machines now 20–25 years old entering the first mechanical service window. Drum rollers ($280–350), belt ($260–320), first thermal fuse failures. ThinQ-enabled LG machines in some of the newer Amerige Heights builds.</p>

